1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:01:28,655
Patient speech can become a clinician-ready draft when staff review stays in control.

2
00:01:28,655 --> 00:02:42,263
The report surface should stay linear, visible, and easy to correct.

3
00:02:42,263 --> 00:03:59,052
ASR transcribes, the LLM structures, and staff review turns the draft into usable intake.

4
00:03:59,052 --> 00:05:14,065
The first bottleneck is a fragmented patient story before clinical reasoning begins.

5
00:05:14,065 --> 00:05:48,919
Speech becomes useful when transcript, uncertainty, and missing questions travel together.

6
00:05:48,919 --> 00:07:06,289
Healthcare AI is realistic when each tool owns the right workflow layer.

7
00:07:06,289 --> 00:08:13,500
Clinical decision-making needs stronger validation than fluent medical text.

8
00:08:13,500 --> 00:09:23,230
A useful clinical model is evaluated on the workflow job it claims to support.

9
00:09:23,230 --> 00:10:12,771
General ability opens the path, but task adaptation and review data make it dependable.

10
00:10:12,771 --> 00:11:25,369
The review decision node is the safety center of the whole architecture.

11
00:11:25,369 --> 00:12:12,692
The system may prepare a review draft; clinical authority remains human.

12
00:12:12,692 --> 00:13:26,207
The useful output is a checkable patient story with uncertainty and missing questions.

13
00:13:26,207 --> 00:14:22,365
Trust comes from layered validation: ASR, structuring, review, workflow, and governance.

14
00:14:22,365 --> 00:15:40,895
The next validation path is staff-reviewed intake support, not an autonomous AI doctor.
